    {
      "content": "Are these virtual machines the same as Hyper-V virtual machines?",
      "pos": [
        3378,
        3442
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In many ways they’re similar to “Generation 1” Hyper-V VMs, but they’re not exactly the same.",
      "pos": [
        3444,
        3537
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Both types provide virtualized hardware, and the VHD-format virtual hard disks are compatible.",
      "pos": [
        3538,
        3632
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means you can move them between Hyper-V and Azure.",
      "pos": [
        3633,
        3688
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Three key differences that sometimes surprise Hyper-V users are:",
      "pos": [
        3689,
        3753
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure doesn’t provide console access to a virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        3757,
        3815
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure VMs in most <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>sizes<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-size-specs.md)</ept> have only 1 virtual network adapter, which means that they also can have only 1 external IP address.",
      "pos": [
        3818,
        3976
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "(The A8 and A9 sizes use a second network adapter for application communication between instances in limited scenarios.)",
      "pos": [
        3977,
        4097
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure VMs don't support Generation 2 Hyper-V VM features.",
      "pos": [
        4100,
        4157
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For details about these features, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Machine Specifications for Hyper-V<ept id=\"p1\">](http://technet.microsoft.com/library/dn592184.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4158,
        4293
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can these virtual machines use my existing, on-premises networking infrastructure?",
      "pos": [
        4298,
        4380
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For virtual machines created in Service Management, you can use Azure Virtual Network to extend your existing infrastructure.",
      "pos": [
        4382,
        4507
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The approach is like setting up a branch office.",
      "pos": [
        4508,
        4556
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can provision and manage virtual private networks (VPNs) in Azure as well as securely connect these to on-premises IT infrastructure.",
      "pos": [
        4557,
        4694
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For details, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Network Overview<ept id=\"p1\">](../virtual-network/virtual-networks-overview.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4695,
        4788
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You’ll need to specify the network that you want the virtual machine to belong to when you create the virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        4790,
        4908
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means, for example, that you can’t join an existing virtual machine to a virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        4909,
        5003
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, you can work around this by detaching the virtual hard disk (VHD) from the existing virtual machine, and then use it to create a new virtual machine with the networking configuration you want.",
      "pos": [
        5004,
        5205
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How can I access  my virtual machine?",
      "pos": [
        5210,
        5247
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to establish a remote connection to log on to the virtual machine, using Remote Desktop Connection for a Windows VM or a Secure Shell (SSH) for a Linux VM.",
      "pos": [
        5249,
        5413
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For instructions, see:",
      "pos": [
        5414,
        5436
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to Log on to a Virtual Machine Running Windows Server<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-log-on-windows-server.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5440,
        5543
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A maximum of 2 concurrent connections are supported, unless the server is configured as a Remote Desktop Services session host.",
      "pos": [
        5544,
        5671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to Log on to a Virtual Machine Running Linux<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-linux-how-to-log-on.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5676,
        5768
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, SSH allows a maximum of 10 concurrent connections.",
      "pos": [
        5769,
        5831
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can increase this number by editing the configuration file.",
      "pos": [
        5832,
        5895
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you’re having problems with Remote Desktop or SSH, install and use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>VMAccess<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=396856)</ept> extension to help fix the problem.",
      "pos": [
        5897,
        6065
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For Windows VMs, additional options include:",
      "pos": [
        6066,
        6110
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6114,
        6212
      ],
      "content": "In the Azure Preview Portal, find the VM, then click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Reset Remote Access<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> from the Command bar."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6215,
        6366
      ],
      "content": "Review <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Troubleshoot Remote Desktop connections to a Windows-based Azure Virtual Machine<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-troubleshoot-remote-desktop-connections.md)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Use Windows PowerShell Remoting to connect to the VM, or create additional endpoints for other resources to connect to the VM.",
      "pos": [
        6369,
        6495
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For details, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to Set Up Endpoints to a Virtual Machine<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-set-up-endpoints.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        6496,
        6598
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you’re familiar with Hyper-V, you might be looking for a tool similar to Virtual Machine Connection.",
      "pos": [
        6600,
        6703
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure doesn’t offer a similar tool because console access to a virtual machine isn’t supported.",
      "pos": [
        6704,
        6799
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can I use the D: drive (Windows) or /dev/sdb1 (Linux)?",
      "pos": [
        6804,
        6858
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You shouldn’t use the D: drive (Windows) or /dev/sdb1 (Linux).",
      "pos": [
        6860,
        6922
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They provide temporary storage only, so you would risk losing data that can’t be recovered.",
      "pos": [
        6923,
        7014
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A common way this could occur is when the virtual machine moves to a different host.",
      "pos": [
        7015,
        7099
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Resizing a virtual machine, updating the host, or a hardware failure on the host are some of the reasons a virtual machine might move.",
      "pos": [
        7100,
        7234
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How can I change the drive letter of the temporary disk?",
      "pos": [
        7239,
        7295
