    {
      "content": "How can I upgrade the guest operating system?",
      "pos": [
        7613,
        7658
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The term upgrade generally means moving to a more recent release of your operating system, while staying on the same hardware.",
      "pos": [
        7660,
        7786
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For Azure VMs, the process for moving to a more recent release differs for Linux and Windows:",
      "pos": [
        7787,
        7880
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For Linux VMs, use the package management tools and procedures appropriate for the distribution.",
      "pos": [
        7884,
        7980
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For a Windows virtual machine, use Windows Server Migration Tools.",
      "pos": [
        7983,
        8049
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Don’t attempt to upgrade the guest OS while it resides on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        8050,
        8114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It isn’t supported because of the risk of losing access to a virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        8115,
        8192
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If problems occur during the upgrade, you could lose the ability to start a Remote Desktop session and wouldn’t be able to troubleshoot the problems.",
      "pos": [
        8193,
        8342
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For general details about the tools and process, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Migrate Roles and Features to Windows Server<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=396940)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8343,
        8492
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For details on upgrading to Windows Server 2012 R2, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Upgrade Options for Windows Server 2012 R2<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/dn303416.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
